<l>maṉṉaṉ karikāl vaḷavaṉīṅ kiyanā</l>
<l>ḷinnakar pōlvatō riyalpiṉa tākip </l>
<l>poṉṉakar vaṟitāp pōtuva reṉpatu</l>
<l>toṉṉilai yuṇarntōr tuṇiporu ḷātaliṟ</l>

        </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <p>1.1-9 (9 lines) The Aetiology of the Indra Festival: The Cōḻa King Cempiyaṉ, on the
            command of the sage Akattiyaṉ, requests Lord Indra to come to stay in the Cōḻa city of
            Kāvirippūmpaṭṭiṉam for the 28 days of the Indra festival. Lord Indra consents. </p>
          <l corresp="3"> When the man of rare penance (the sage Akattiyaṉ) commanded it [from his
            seat on] towering Mount Potiyam— </l>
          <l corresp="2bc"> in order that the qualities of the ancient city (Kāvirippūmpaṭṭiṉam) </l>
          <l corresp="1-2a"> extolled by many people [and] of sublime, towering
            fame/beauty/superiority/prosperity unchanging [in the eyes] of the world</l>
          <l corresp="2d"> become [even more] widely known – </l>
          <l corresp="4"> Cempiyaṉ (a Cōḻa king) of the shoulder-bangles, who destroyed the hanging
            fortresses,</l>
          <l corresp="5"> standing bowed before the Lord of the Celestials (Indra), addressed [him]: </l>
          <l corresp="6ab"> 'May he who is [well] spoken of on earth (Indra) </l>
          <l corresp="6cd, 8"> dwell very sweetly in the/his heavenly city (Kāvirippūmpaṭṭiṉam) for
            the twenty-eight days </l>
          <l corresp="7"> during which the festival is held—since those on high (i.e. the gods)
            desire [it]!'</l>
          <l corresp="9"> Thereupon the Lord of the Immortals (Indra) consented to that [request]. </l>

          <p>1.10-18ab (19 lines) The Vedic scholars of Kāvirippūmpaṭṭiṉam approve the festival.
            Different groups—religious experts, astrologers, the gods disguised as humans,
            people of different linguistic groups, the king's ministers and retinue—pour into
            the city.</p>

          <l corresp="10"> [And] since the scholars of the ungraspable Vedas did not gainsay [this
            edict]—</l>
          <l corresp="13ab-12cd"> the religious experts [of Kāvirippūmpaṭṭiṉam], who show the nature
            of those</l>
          <l corresp="12ab"> various different doctrines which deal with/which are known as: </l>
          <l corresp="11"> epistemology, custom (i.e. secular literature?) [and] the good tenets of
            liberation; </l>
          <l corresp="14ab-13cd"> and the astrologers (lit. time-counters), who follow their
            domain(s) </l>
          <l corresp="14cd"> did not leave [the city];</l>
          <l corresp="15"> and the gods, who had taken on [human] forms as a disguise, </l>
          <l corresp="16">and people of [different] tongues who had gathered together, spreading
            [everywhere in the city];</l>
          <l corresp="17-18ab"> and the five great [royal] councils and the eight great groups
            [forming the royal retinue] arrived, crowding all together; </l>
          
            <p>18cd-26 (9 lines) For fear of inciting the hostility of the bhūta, the assembled
              groups resolve to perform the festival.</p>

          <l corresp="18cd, 20cd">[And they] resolved: 'If [we] forget to hold the festival in [our]
            heavenly city, </l>
          <l corresp="19-20ab">the bhūta who freed the victorious-king
            (Mucukunta) with armies and chariots with banners from [his] misery </l>
          <l corresp="22">will cause [us] affliction with the roaring sound of thunder, </l>
          <l corresp="21">while the strong teeth in his red mouth with its pursed [lips] flash.</l>
          <l corresp="23-24">[This] bhūta, who will beat and eat the sinners of [our] ancient city
            whom
            it will capture in [its] noose, will become hostile [to us].</l>
          <l corresp="25-26">[Therefore] let the festival to the thousand-eyed one (Indra), in which
            the supreme monarchs of the great, vast earth are gathered, commence!' </l>
            
            <p>1.27-31 The drummer beats the drum of Indra to summon Yama and proclaim the festival.</p>

<l corresp="31">            The man born of an ancient clan beats with a stick the drum—</l>
<l corresp="27">the union-drum (i.e. festival drum?) from the enclosure of the thunderbolt (i.e. Indra's temple),  </l>
<l corresp="28">mounted on the nape of an elephant [wearing] a belt, </l>
<l corresp="29">wrapped in a bull hide, with a thunderous roar, </l>
<l corresp="30">with blood-lust, summoning Yama—[and proclaims:]</l>




        </lg>
      </div>
